arch:property.oc:show_val: Rock feature with mortar in the SE 1/4 of the trench. The mortar is a curved stone(not BOWL) that sits in the middle of the rock pile. One rock has striations that are similar to the natural striations found on other rocks in the area. this locus is cut into the wall. There are pottery in this locus although we do not have that many in the wall. Also The texture is looser than the walls as the color is darker with a reddih stress. When we came to the end of the first course of the wall we changed the locus to L4047 arbitrarily in order to avoid mixing stuff.
Rocks covered but hard packed silty dirt
very compact material There are 8 stones of varying shapes and sizes, including one stone that appears to be a curved matate (grinding stone)

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.

arch:property.oc:show_val: a pit cut into the wall, L4030, that seems like a rock pile in the beginning but we saw in the section of the wall that it is a pit.
